idates like en_US and the base correctly. For Locale.GERMANY, the fallback will naturally exclude en_US and use the proper de_DE instead.\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.glassfish.grizzly:grizzly-http:2.1.2/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-09T01-43-49-104253Z.log:806:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering test framework and classes**\\n\\nI’m thinking about maintaining a clear one-to-one mapping between the report classes and the test class files. There’s a question around the Grizzly_httpTest placeholder—whether to remove it since it might not map correctly. The user asked for the active class only, so it’s important to consider how to approach these placeholders.\\n\\nI'll need to ensure compatibility with the JUnit Jupiter framework and the AssertJ library, maybe needing to clear some ResourceBundle caches. Also, I’m pondering how to make sure the tests pass under Native Image after the necessary metadata is generated.\\n\\n**Thinking about ResourceBundle configuration**\\n\\nI’m considering how to set up ResourceBundle properly with the test resources, especially for Native Image. The included resource bundles should rely on generated metadata under build/native/generated, and I need to ensure the resource config isn't inadvertently modified. I'll write the resources in src/test/resources, which is allowed. \\n\\nTo prevent fallback issues, I plan to create just the LocalStrings_en_US.properties file. This way, for Locale.US, it finds the correct candidates like en_US and the base correctly. For Locale.GERMANY, the fallback will naturally exclude en_US and use the proper de_DE instead.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_00ae4f13980729570169fe9116f77c81909a35eca69fd3d222\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp_pEjbqOJixRSi1wNSmOQpXJ8_35wNZCMBIebfskIJ1JD4_9rokNf1XtuaqzL_C57rw_X9cIIdMPIIT2BmEkNso1i8dHS8vwyrc